issue.title: Improvement: Make local server generate client leave messages more similarly to real services

***DO NOT MERGE THIS PR USING THE GITHUB UI.***

The aim of this pull request is to sync main and next branch. If this PR is assigned to you, you need to do the following:

1. Acknowledge the pull request by adding a comment -- "Actively working on it".
2. If there are no CI failures, add the "msftbot: merge-next" label to the PR and one of the people with merge permissions will merge it in.
3. If there ***are*** CI failures, check out the main-next-1634344 branch and make code changes to fix the failures.
  - You can ignore any failures in the **Real service e2e test** and **Stress test** pipelines. These pipelines are not required to pass to merge changes.

issue.title: fix(tree2): Make at() in Sequence match semantics of Array.prototype.at()

labels.name: area: dds
labels.description: Issues related to distributed data structures

issue.body:
## Description

Makes `Sequence`'s `at()` method match the semantics of [`Array.prototype.at()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/at) for negative indices or out-of-bounds access. 

## Breaking Changes

`Sequence`'s `at()` method can now return undefined for out-of-bound access and behaves differently for negative indices.

## Reviewer Guidance

The review process is outlined on [this wiki page](https://github.com/microsoft/FluidFramework/wiki/PR-Guidelines#guidelines).

I did not want to change the signature and behavior of `LazyField.at()` thinking it might require a lot of additional asserting and that the semantics of doing that on a generic field might be better served with more strict constraints, so I renamed it to `atIndex()`. But seems like it's not used in many places, so if people think it's better to make it behave like `Sequence.at()` I can do that and avoid the extra method.

pull_request.title: feat(build-cli): Add support for selecting only changed packages
pull_request.body:
Adds a selection flag that can be used to select packages that have changed when compared to a base branch. The intended use case is this:

```shell
flub exec --changed -- "npm run format"
```

That command will run `npm run format` in all packages that have changes since `main`.

The base branch can be changed using the `--branch` flag:

```
flub exec --changed --branch next -- "npm run format"
```
